defaultWritten evidence submitted by E3G (CCS33)default1. Summarydefault1.1
default              
defaultThe current UK approach to CCS is too narrowly focussed on electricity 
defaultgeneration and the procurement of individual projects. This must be urgently supplemented by a view on what ultimate deployment of CCS could look like in a decarbonised economy, and the necessary practical actions that are required to enable this to be ach
defaultieved.
default1.2
default              
defaultThe Office of CCS within DECC is tied down in ‘delivery’ mode. While recognising that it is seeking to do a difficult task with 
defaultreduced
default funding, it is failing to catalyse the parallel efforts in enabling infrastructure and industrial CCS require
defaultd to enable wider deployment and cost reduction. The OCCS is also responsible for fossil fuel 
defaultstrategy
default, but CCS is insufficiently integrated into current policies – particularly the gas strategy and the prospects for continued use of coal. 
default1.3
default              
defaultUK policy o
defaultn CCS appears to reflect a fear of being seen to be ‘picking winners’
default: the first UK competition picked a technology option and suffered for it. We would therefore agree that maintaining openness to different capture technologies should be continued. Howeve
defaultr it is imperative that a more proactive approach be taken to ‘pick geologies’ (for large-scale storage) and ‘pick geographies’ (for infrastructure investment).
default This will provide the largest benefits to the UK via cost reduction, the retention of industria
defaultl jobs and the development of exportable CCS engineering and integration expertise.
default1.4
default              
defaultPrevious UK leadership on CCS in Europe and internationally has been diminished over recent years. The UK needs to ensure that it secures funding from the second round 
defaultof the NER300 mechanism, and should be taking a more proactive approach to EU policy discussions. The introduction of a CCS certificate system (or similar) could bring significant benefits for UK projects.
